In 2016, Google took down 1.7 billion ads in an effort to protect people from misleading, inappropriate, or harmful marketing. “Bad ads can ruin the online experience for everyone. They promote illegal products and unrealistic offers,” said Google. These ads can also trick people into sharing personal information and infect devices with malware. “Ultimately, bad ads pose a threat to users, Google’s partners, and the sustainability of the open web itself.” Google’s set of ad policies govern the types of ads it allows on its platforms. “We have a team of engineers, policy experts, product managers, and others who are waging a daily fight against bad actors.” Google’s 2016 figures related to bad ads include: